<br>
Nirtox said &quot;As an example: DMs killed Aary at 10pm our time, went into NToV till 12am, then people who have to get up next morning (you realise that people do have work, don't you???) logged off. On the next day DMs had around 25 people with 1 warrior and 2 clerics, so we made the choice to fool around with Dain pull and not go into NToV. If we had enough people for NToV, it would have been nice to get a decent info from any other guild who wants to go in, that they intend to do so if DMs won't show up and do it. Secretly spying on DMs struggles in Icewell (man, what fun  ) and then telling lies about having killed Aary themselves is not what I call decent human behaviour. &quot;<br>
<br>
  Thats exactly what i said, only longwinded. A guild went into NTOV, killed Aary, was tired and left. The following day, they elected not to return to NToV and went to do other content, for whatever reason. <br>
<br>
  All the complaints im hearing here, are in relation to a guild not respecting the &quot;temporary ownership&quot; of a wing of TOV due to that guild having killed the gate keeper the day before.<br>
<br>
  Im sorry, that does not make any sense.<br>
<br>
  ToV as so noted, is no longer a 100 man 15 hour raid as other posts mentioned. I believe this &quot;unspoken rule&quot; to be a relic of that era, and as such, it should be rewritten.<br>
<br>
  I would like to suggest the following as an update to that rule:<br>
<br>
*If you have the force to kill aary, then kill him.<br>
*If you have the force to kill aary, and then sweep NToV, then do so.<br>
*If you have the force to kill Aaary, but run out of time to do the rest of the wing, so be it.Do Aary and then move on.<br>
<br>
*If you do not have the time or the forces to do any, go do something else.<br>
<br>
  Simple. Fair. Easy. Logical.<br>
<br>
  Times change. People come and go. Rules are made, enforced, rewitten, broken, and amended, each and every day.<br>
<br>
  I dont really get where the orginal rule came from, i mean your there, your ready, you do it. You lack forces, you lack organization, you lack motivation, you loose.<br>
<br>
  As always, i am speaking for myself, not the guild to which i belong.<br>
